📖 Theory
What is systemd?

systemd is the init system used by modern Linux distributions. It starts services during boot and manages them while the system is running.

Examples of services:

ssh
docker
nginx
jenkins
cron
🛠️ Task 1 – List Running Services
systemctl list-units --type=service

Only failed services:

systemctl --failed
🛠️ Task 2 – Check Service Status
systemctl status ssh

or

systemctl status cron
🛠️ Task 3 – Start, Stop & Restart
sudo systemctl start ssh

sudo systemctl stop ssh

sudo systemctl restart ssh

sudo systemctl reload ssh
🛠️ Task 4 – Enable/Disable at Boot

Enable:

sudo systemctl enable ssh

Disable:

sudo systemctl disable ssh

Verify:

systemctl is-enabled ssh
🛠️ Task 5 – Check Boot Time
systemd-analyze

Detailed startup analysis:

systemd-analyze blame
🛠️ Task 6 – View Logs

Entire journal:

journalctl

Last boot:

journalctl -b

Logs for SSH:

journalctl -u ssh

Last 20 lines:

journalctl -u ssh -n 20

Follow logs live:

journalctl -f
🛠️ Task 7 – Create a Custom Service

Create:

sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/devops-demo.service

Paste:

[Unit]
Description=DevOps Demo Service

[Service]
ExecStart=/bin/bash /home/$USER/devops-demo.sh
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

Create script:

nano ~/devops-demo.sh
#!/bin/bash

while true
do
echo "DevOps Service Running"
sleep 30
done

Make executable:

chmod +x ~/devops-demo.sh

Reload:

sudo systemctl daemon-reload

Start:

sudo systemctl start devops-demo

Status:

systemctl status devops-demo

Enable:

sudo systemctl enable devops-demo
